<font color="#FF0000">I HEAR YOU MY BROTHER!!!!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 31 20:47:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Mustang Two Four,<br><br>
It has been an honor to have joined such a crowd.  We share on this site the same way I see the Veterans of Foreign Wars share in their weekly mettings.  It helps to understand the change that was made in us all.  I never leave a friend.   I call few people my friends in life and I honor all that I do.  I found friends on this site and you most assuredly are one of those.  I find our spirits are destined to take the same path.<br><br>
I was invited to take part in this site when it was founded.  I knew I had strong feelings and always kept them to myself.  We have talked of this before.  I have been here and watched the site grow and move in the wind like bambo in the monsoons.  Different factions pushing for strength.  The binding together of men of a common conscious has occured.<br><br>
Not so long ago the site begin to struggle under the weight of a single antagonist.  That person was Doc Spatz.  A very dear friend of mine who has a vested interest in this site asked me to consider participation.  Without the diatribe and haranguing of Spatz I might have remained silent.  Ed I am that Spook friend that Arthur spoke of.  You understand what he meant I am sure.  I have touched all the services and do at this moment as a civilian.  I have been privileged to be places and do things that others have dreamed of.  I would like to share those with you and a chosen few.  I have no regrets.  All my warrior life was not Vietnam, only a small part although three years and several hundred combat missions seemed like a lot at the time.<br><br>
Spatz caught me off guard when he mentioned the new comers were destroying the site.  I responded too quickly, an error I am not used to making, but I did.  Sorry.<br><br>
I have watched you guys take back your dignity and refuse to let others tarnish your pride.  It bothers them, especially Spatz.  Their has even been a tolerance of sorts allowed the Doc.  I am not totally convinced we were correct, but no gain without risk.  We have always been risk takers.  That is the fabric of a Warrior.<br><br>
I have read a post of Doc's on another thread and again digested what he wrote last night.  I think he has made a grave mistake.<br><br>
I spent the day at an Army post.  Armor and Apache gunships.  Large color photos on the wall hung in pride of a foot soldier with his M60 and a door gunner in a Huey with a mini gun at full song.  It made me remember we are not relics of the past.  Our values remain and our experiences have resulted in new training.  We were and are part of the future.  I grew up as a youngster with a neighbor on one side who was Patton's head of armor in Africa and A Marine who was a POW in Korea.  They talked I listened.  I could re-write the Patton story.  Nothing has changed.<br><br>
Ed I'll throttle back just long enough for you to take a tow.  Then watch out for the airspeed gain.  We are going for one hell of a ride.
<p><code>--   (Silent Warrior) </code><p>


